### 2. The Motherhood Penalty

One of the most significant contributors to the gender pay gap is the "motherhood penalty," whereby women experience wage reductions and career setbacks after having children. Research shows that women’s earnings decline by approximately 4% for each child they have, while men often receive a "fatherhood bonus," with earnings increasing after becoming fathers ([Blau & Kahn, 2016](https://www.nber.org/papers/w21913); [Correll, Benard, & Paik, 2007](https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.1086/521818)).

Employers may perceive mothers as less committed or competent, leading to fewer promotions, lower starting salaries, and exclusion from challenging assignments. Experimental studies reveal that identical job applications are rated lower when the applicant is a mother, but not when the applicant is a father ([Correll et al., 2007](https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.1086/521818)).

### 3. Differences in Work Experience and Hours

Women often have less continuous work experience than men due to caregiving responsibilities, leading to gaps in employment history and fewer hours worked. On average, men work about 41 hours per week, while women work approximately 36.3 hours ([InHerSight, 2019](https://www.inhersight.com/blog/why-the-gender-pay-gap-exists-according-to-research)). These differences affect wage accumulation and career progression.

Moreover, women are more likely to take part-time jobs or leave the workforce temporarily, which impacts their long-term earnings and retirement savings. For example, a woman earning $44,000 annually who takes five years off for caregiving may lose over $700,000 in lifetime earnings when considering lost wages and retirement contributions ([CBS News, 2018](https://www.cbsnews.com/news/4-ways-women-earn-less-than-men/)).

### 4. Discrimination and Bias

Despite legal prohibitions, gender discrimination persists in hiring, pay, and promotion decisions. Studies using audit methods and controlled experiments demonstrate that women are often evaluated less favorably than men with identical qualifications, particularly when they are mothers ([Correll et al., 2007](https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.1086/521818)).

Biases include:

- **Maternal Wall Bias**: Negative assumptions about mothers’ commitment and competence.
- **Commitment Double Bind**: Women need higher qualifications to prove competence but are simultaneously perceived as less committed.
- **Negotiation Penalties**: Women are less likely to negotiate salaries and may face backlash when they do ([InHerSight, 2019](https://www.inhersight.com/blog/why-the-gender-pay-gap-exists-according-to-research)).

### 5. Societal Norms and Cultural Expectations

Cultural norms about gender roles significantly influence career choices and workplace dynamics. The expectation that women should prioritize caregiving and men should be breadwinners shapes occupational segregation, work hours, and employer perceptions ([Scarborough & Moeder, 2022](https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/00031224221077086)).

These norms also affect parental leave policies and workplace flexibility, often disadvantaging women who need accommodations for family responsibilities.

